    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-pump-piv-dataset-2013",
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/morrison-mcq-uq-ensemble-2024",
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/leverett-hemolysis-correlation-1972"
  ],
  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to predict absolute hemolysis levels across operating conditions for a centrifugal blood pump used as a ventricular assist device (VAD). Model influence is HIGH (model is primary basis for hemolysis acceptance); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect prediction could result in chronic patient hemolysis requiring clinical intervention). Model Risk Level 5 — the highest in the Morrison assessment.",
    "deviceClass": "Class III",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou2-vad",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to predict absolute hemolysis index values for a Class III VAD device across 5 flow-speed combinations. Results must demonstrate hemolysis below absolute clinical threshold (not relative to predicate). Requires Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification on hemolysis predictions.",
    "modelInfluence": "High",
    "name": "COU2: Ventricular assist device use (Class III)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/no-comparator",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Primary hemolysis output comparison — fixed-speed experimental reference",
      "description": "The CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (nIH) was evaluated against in-vitro measurements reported by Graefe et al. (2022), who instrumented a geometrically identical centrifugal pump housing with inline plasma-free haemoglobin sampling across a 90-minute recirculation protocol. Graefe et al. report nIH values of 0.0031 ± 0.0004 g/100 L at 3000 RPM / 5 L/min, the nominal design point. The CFD model predicts nIH = 0.0029 g/100 L at this condition, yielding a relative error of 6.5%, which falls within the declared acceptance band of ±15%. The experimental protocol is considered high quality: blood analogue fluid was bovine blood with haematocrit 33 ± 1%, temperature controlled to 37 °C, and shear exposure time was tracked via particle residence-time distributions consistent with the Lagrangian damage accumulation approach used in the CFD post-processor. On the basis of this agreement at the nominal operating point, the Output Comparison factor is assessed as satisfactory. The Graefe et al. dataset is widely cited in the pump haemolysis literature and represents a rigorous experimental benchmark. No further operating-point comparisons were performed because the dataset was collected exclusively at 3000 RPM; the four additional flow-speed combinations required by the COU (2400 RPM / 3 L/min, 2400 RPM / 6 L/min, 3600 RPM / 4 L/min, and 3600 RPM / 7 L/min) lie outside the experimental scope of this reference. The inference that model fidelity demonstrated at the nominal point generalises to off-design points with different impeller tip speeds and blade-passage shear histories is stated implicitly but not substantiated by additional comparator data."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/verification-code-check",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Numerical code verification against method-of-manufactured-solutions benchmark",
      "description": "A method-of-manufactured-solutions (MMS) test was applied to the incompressible Navier-Stokes solver (ANSYS Fluent 2023 R1, double precision) using a rotating annular domain with an analytically prescribed velocity field. Observed order of accuracy was 1.97 for velocity magnitude and 1.94 for pressure, consistent with the nominal second-order spatial discretisation. Residual convergence to 1e-6 was achieved in all cases.",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/mms-rotating-annulus-analytical-solution-v1"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/piv-velocity-comparison",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Velocity field validation against FDA pump PIV dataset",
      "description": "Ensemble-averaged velocity components in the impeller passage and volute were compared against the FDA 2013 PIV dataset (Stewart et al.) at 2500 RPM / 6 L/min. Mean absolute error in axial velocity was 4.2% of tip speed; radial velocity error was 6.1%. Agreement is within the uncertainty bounds of the PIV measurements (±5% of tip speed at 95% confidence). This comparison supports the flow-field fidelity of the CFD model but does not directly address hemolysis-relevant shear stress distributions at the VAD operating speeds specified in the COU.",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-pump-piv-dataset-2013"
