      "rationale": "Richardson extrapolation was performed at the nominal 3000 RPM / 5 L/min operating point using meshes of 4.2 M, 9.8 M, and 21.4 M cells. GCI for nIH was 3.8% at this point. Grid convergence studies were not repeated at the four off-design operating points required by the COU; discretization error at those conditions is unquantified. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions used for validation must span the full operating envelope defined by the COU (five flow-speed combinations); fluid properties, temperature, and haematocrit must be documented and matched in CFD boundary conditions.",
      "rationale": "The Graefe et al. (2022) in-vitro tests were conducted under tightly controlled conditions (bovine blood, Hct 33%, 37 °C) and are well-documented. However, testing was performed exclusively at 3000 RPM / 5 L/min. The four additional COU operating points are not represented in the experimental dataset. Fluid property matching at the nominal point is excellent; extrapolation to off-design conditions is unsupported. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison of CFD-predicted nIH against experimental measurements at all five COU operating points; relative error must be within ±15% at each point; uncertainty intervals must be propagated from both simulation and experiment.",
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison was performed at the nominal operating point (3000 RPM / 5 L/min), yielding a relative error of 6.5%, within the ±15% acceptance band. The experimental reference (Graefe et al. 2022) is a high-quality dataset with well-characterised measurement uncertainty. Agreement at this single point is taken as indicative of model fidelity across the operating envelope, but no direct comparisons exist at the four off-design conditions. The inference that single-point agreement validates multi-point predictive capability constitutes an undercutting inference-method mismatch: the comparator is appropriate in kind but mismatched in scope to the declared COU. Achieved level 3 against required level 4."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The primary QoI (nIH) must be directly comparable to the clinical hemolysis threshold; secondary QoIs (shear stress, residence time) must be shown to be sensitive indicators of hemolysis at COU conditions.",
      "rationale": "nIH is the standard hemolysis metric in ASTM F1841 and maps directly to the clinical threshold. The Lagrangian shear-stress integral used in the CFD post-processor has been validated for nIH prediction in the literature. Sensitivity of nIH to impeller speed is well-established, but sensitivity analyses in this package were performed only at the nominal speed. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must collectively address the full COU operating envelope; any extrapolation beyond the validated domain must be explicitly justified with supporting sensitivity or uncertainty analysis.",
      "rationale": "The validation activities address geometry (identical pump housing), fluid (bovine blood analogue), and the nominal operating point. They do not address the four additional flow-speed combinations in the COU. Extrapolation to off-design impeller speeds introduces speed-dependent blade-passage shear histories that have not been validated. No formal extrapolation justification or sensitivity analysis was provided for off-design conditions. Achieved level 2, two gradations below the required level 4."
    },
